Interview Questions
1) What is a switch statement in Java?
-->A switch statement is a selection control statement used to execute one block of code among many based on the value of a variable.
    👉 It is mainly used as an alternative to multiple if-else conditions when comparing one variable with fixed values.




2) What is the syntax of a switch statement?
-->switch (expression) {
      case value1:
          // code
          break;
      case value2:
          // code
          break;
      default:
          // code
  }



3) What is the purpose of the break keyword in a switch?
-->The break statement is used to terminate the switch block after a case is executed.
    👉 Without break, execution continues to the next cases.



4) What happens if break is omitted in a switch-case?
-->👉 It causes fall-through behavior.

      int x = 2;
      
      switch(x) {
          case 1:
              System.out.println("One");
          case 2:
              System.out.println("Two");
          case 3:
              System.out.println("Three");
      }
      
      👉 Output:
      
      Two
      Three



5) Can we use multiple statements inside a case block?
-->✅ Yes
    case 1:
        System.out.println("Hello");
        System.out.println("World");
        break;


6) What is the purpose of the default case? Is the default case mandatory in a switch?
-->default executes when no case matches
    It is optional, not mandatory


7) Can default be written anywhere in the switch block?
-->✅ Yes  👉 But best practice is to place it at the end.



8) How does Java decide which case to execute?
-->👉 Java:
    Evaluates the switch expression
    Compares it with each case value
    Executes the matching case
    
    👉 Matching is based on exact value (== comparison)


9) Can two case labels have the same constant value?
-->❌ No  👉 It results in a compile-time error (duplicate case label)


10) Which primitive data types are supported in switch?
-->✅ Supported:
    byte
    short
    char
    int
    
    ✅ Also supported:
    String (since Java 7)
    enum
    Wrapper classes like Integer, Character
    
    ❌ Not supported:
    long
    float
    double
    boolean




11) How is a switch expression different from a switch statement?
-->
| Feature       | Switch Statement | Switch Expression (Java 12+) |
| ------------- | ---------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Syntax        | `case:`          | `case ->`                    |
| Break needed  | Yes              | No                           |
| Fall-through  | Yes              | No (by default)              |
| Returns value | No               | Yes                          |
| Usage         | Control flow     | Assign values                |

👉 Example:
      int result = switch(day) {
          case 1 -> 100;
          case 2 -> 200;
          default -> 0;
      };
